Basic Bulleted List
\begin{itemize}
    \item This is the first bullet point.
    \item This is the second bullet point.
    \item This is the third bullet point.
\end{itemize}

Automatic Numbering in Lists

\begin{enumerate}
    \item The first item.
    \item The second item.
    \item The number changes automatically when items are added or removed.
\end{enumerate}

Nested Bullet Points
\begin{itemize}
    \item Top level item
    \begin{itemize}
        \item A second level nested item
        \item Another second level nested item
    \end{itemize}
    \item Back to main bullet list
\end{itemize}

Customizing Bullet Points
\begin{itemize}
    \item[$\circ$] This item has an open circle bullet.
    \item[$\ast$] This item has an asterisk bullet.
    \item[-] This item uses a dash.
\end{itemize}


Using the enumitem Package
The enumitem package offers easy customization of list labels. You can specify the label format in an optional argument to the \begin{enumerate} command. 
Include the package in your document's preamble:
latex
\usepackage{enumitem}
Create the list using the enumerate environment and specify the label format with label={...}:
For lowercase letters (a, b, c...):
latex
\begin{enumerate}[label={\alph*)}]
  \item An apple
  \item A banana
  \item A carrot
\end{enumerate}
This will produce items labeled as a), b), c), etc.
For uppercase letters (A, B, C...):
latex
\begin{enumerate}[label={\Alph*}]
  \item The first item
  \item The second item
  \item The third item
\end{enumerate}
This will produce items labeled as A, B, C, etc.
For parentheses around the letter, like (a), (b), (c):
latex
\begin{enumerate}[label={(\alph*)}]
  \item A condition
  \item Another condition
  \item A final condition
\end{enumerate}